T1  - PPP EXCHANGE RATE RULES, MACROECONOMIC (IN)STABILITY, AND LEARNING*
AU  - Zanna, Luis-Felipe
Y1  - 2009/11/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/11/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2009.00561.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1103
EP  - 1128
VL  - 50
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2009.00561.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - In order to maintain competitiveness, governments in developing economies seem to have pursued purchasing power parity (PPP) exchange rate rules, by adjusting the nominal devaluation rate in response to real exchange rate deviations from an intermediate target. This article shows that these rules are likely to induce macroeconomic instability, as they generate sunspot-driven fluctuations that are in fact learnable by agents in the Expectational-Stability sense. It finds that the existence of these ?learnable sunspots? depends, among others, on open economy features, including the degree of openness and the degree of exchange rate pass-through to consumer's import prices.
ER  - 

