T1  - HETEROGENEOUS BORROWERS IN QUANTITATIVE MODELS OF SOVEREIGN DEFAULT*
AU  - Hatchondo, Juan Carlos
AU  - Martinez, Leonardo
AU  - Sapriza, Horacio
Y1  - 2009/11/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/11/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2009.00562.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1129
EP  - 1151
VL  - 50
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2009.00562.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We extend the model used in recent quantitative studies of sovereign default, allowing policymakers of different types to stochastically alternate in power. We show that a default episode may be triggered by a change in the type of policymaker in office, and that such a default is likely to occur only if there is enough political stability and if policymakers encounter poor economic conditions. Under high political stability, political turnover enables the model to generate a weaker correlation between economic conditions and default decisions, a higher and more volatile spread, and lower borrowing levels after a default episode.
ER  - 

